[2] USA: New York state, public health travel ban, New Jersey
Date: Thu 28 May 2019 8:02 AM EDT
Source: North Jersey Record [abridged, edited]
https://eu.northjersey.com/story/news/new-jersey/2019/05/27/measles-two-ny-kept-flying-threat-rare-travel-ban/1245994001/


Officials in New York have consulted with federal authorities to help prevent 2 people exposed to measles from traveling by air in an attempt to contain the spread of the disease amid the largest outbreak of the virus in 2 decades, officials confirmed [on Sun 26 May 2019]. The unidentified people are among 8 throughout the country who have voluntarily canceled travel plans in lieu of being placed on a rarely used federal list maintained by CDC that would bar them from boarding flights, according to a report in the Washington Post.

The current outbreak of the virus has its roots in air travel. Several travelers came to the United States legally from Israel, where there are outbreaks of the virus, and visited ultra-Orthodox communities where there is an aversion to vaccinations. "That's how we started here," said Ed Day, the Rockland county executive. "They came in legitimately through the front door."

Outbreak spreads across the county
----------------------------------
Health officials in 5 states, including New York, have contacted CDC about travelers who have been exposed to measles for their potential inclusion on the list, according to the Washington Post.

A total of 880 cases of measles in 24 states [see above -- the most current CDC case count is 940 cases in 26 states] have been reported this year [2019], which is a 25-year high, CDC recently reported. That's the highest annual total since more than 950 cases were reported in 1994. A representative from the CDC did not immediately respond to requests for comment on [Sun 26 May 2019].

The outbreak in Rockland county began when 7 travelers from Israel visited last October [2018]. Since then, the county Health Department, Refuah Health Center, and private pediatricians and family doctors have administered more than 21 000 doses of the measles, mumps, and rubella, or MMR, vaccine since the outbreak started.

Of the people infected in Rockland, 85% have been under 18 years old, Day said. Before the outbreak, there was only a 70% immunization rate in Rockland. "Those numbers are beginning to shift because we've given out so many MMRs," he said. The county typically gives 1000 doses of the MMR vaccine, which is regarded as the best way to stop the spread of the virus, each year.

The 2 people from New York, who were dissuaded from traveling, were identified during routine investigations regarding exposures and infections, Day said. People who are exposed to the virus are warned not to travel, but the 2 people told health investigators that they planned to travel regardless. That's why officials escalated the matter to federal authorities, he said. Day has taken an aggressive stance in attempting to halt the spread of the disease. He has issued 2 orders, one of which was struck down in court, seeking to prevent people infected with measles from attending school and from gathering in public.

Fewer cases so far in New Jersey
--------------------------------
There have been far fewer cases in New Jersey. Only 14 people have been infected: 11 in Lakewood township in Ocean county and 3 people in one Passaic household. However, several exposure warnings have been issued by New Jersey health officials since the outbreak began late last year [2018].

The Do Not Board list was first implemented in 2007 in response to a case of a man traveling to Europe who had been infected with drug-resistant tuberculosis, according to the Washington Post.

Measles exposure warnings in New Jersey are infrequent and limited compared with Rockland county, which last week [week of 20 May 2019] issued a list of a dozen locations, including 2 taxis, used by potentially infected people.

The county executive also wrote to the Trump administration asking for an order to prevent people without immunity to measles from entering the country. Day said he has since been in communication with officials from the federal Department of Health and Human Services, but he declined to talk about the specifics of those conversations.

CDC's Do Not Board list would not prevent people infected with measles from entering the county. Yellow fever is the only disease for which proof of immunization is required and changing that would require a lot of international cooperation, according to the Washington Post.

[byline: Matthew McGrath]

