[7] Canada (New Brunswick)
Date: Sun 26 May 2019
Source: The Globe and Mail, The Canadian Press report [abridged, edited]
https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-two-new-measles-cases-confirmed-in-new-brunswick-bringing-total-to/


Chief medical officer of health, Dr Jennifer Russell, says public health officials in New Brunswick are setting up a special immunization clinic aimed at those in the school population who haven't yet received a dose of vaccine within the last 28 days. Health officials in New Brunswick say there are 2 new cases of measles in the province, bringing the number of confirmed cases to 5.

All of the cases are in the Saint John area and the latest 2, confirmed late [Sat 25 May 2019], are linked to a previous confirmed case at Kennebecasis Valley High School. The latest cases followed news on [Fri 24 May 2019] of another confirmed case, the province's 3rd, which was also linked to the school.

In a news release, Dr Jennifer Russell says public health officials are setting up a special immunization clinic aimed at those in the school population who haven't yet received a dose of vaccine within the last 28 days. A previous immunization clinic was held at the school on [Fri 24 May 2019], and Dr Russell says the new clinic will be offered for added protection as an outbreak control measure because of recent exposures.

On [Fri 24 May 2019], public health officials issued a directive advising staff and students at Kennebecasis Valley High School that they must receive a measles booster shot if they want to continue going to school.

The 1st confirmed case in the Saint John area involved a person who visited the Halifax Infirmary emergency room last month [April 2019] and later went to the ER and X-ray room at Saint John Regional Hospital. Officials later confirmed the 1st infected patient recently travelled internationally. The 2nd case was confirmed at Kennebecasis Valley High School.

[byline: Brian Snyder]

